[[File:Blako 2277 cropped.jpg|thumb|right|''[[Bambusa lako]]'', in [[Sydney]]]] Dr. '''Elizabeth Anita Widjaja''' (born 1951) is a Senior Principal Researcher of [[bamboo]] taxonomy at the [[Herbarium Bogoriense]], Botany Division, Biological Research Centre at the [[Indonesian Institute of Sciences]] in [[Bogor]], [[Indonesia]].<ref name="fao"> {{cite book | url=http://www.fao.org/docrep/V7540E/V7540e10.htm | title=International Expert Consultation on Non-Wood Forest Products | year=1995 | publisher=[[Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations]] | accessdate=2009-04-07 | isbn=92-5-103701-9 }}</ref><ref name="akha"> {{cite web | url=http://www.akha.org/content/bamboo/overstorybamboo.html | title=Plant Resources of South-East Asia No 7. Bamboos. | last=Dransfield | first=Soejatmi |author2=Elizabeth A. Widjaja | year=1995 | publisher=[[Backhuys Publishers]] | pages=189|accessdate=2009-04-07 }}</ref><ref name="bioversityinternational">{{cite web|url=http://www.bioversityinternational.org/publications/Web_version/572/ch26.htm |title=State of the art of Indonesian Bamboo |last=Widjaja |first=Elizabeth A |publisher=[[Bioversity International]] |accessdate=2009-04-07 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205055932/http://www.bioversityinternational.org/publications/Web_version/572/ch26.htm |archivedate=December 5, 2008 }}</ref><ref name="openlibrary"> {{cite web | url=http://openlibrary.org/a/OL4405600A/Elizabeth-Anita-Widjaja | title=Elizabeth Anita Widjaja | publisher=[[Open Library]] | accessdate=2009-04-07 }}</ref> She is especially interested in Indonesian bamboo and [[Malesia]]n bamboo generally, and promotes the cultivation of bamboo for the prevention of [[erosion]].<ref name="akha" />
Dr. Widjaja recently said, of bamboo as a source of [[biofuel]], that:
{{quote|It is an overwhelming source. Furthermore, it is easy to work with bamboo so research about bamboo-based biofuel should be cheaper.<ref> {{cite web | url=http://www.biologi.lipi.go.id/bio_english/news_detail.php?id_berita=63|date=2009-02-07 | title=Biofuel from Bamboo Tree | publisher=Research Center for Biology, [[Indonesian Institute of Sciences]] | accessdate=2009-04-07 }}</ref>}}
''[[Bambusa lako]]'' (Timor black bamboo) was described and separated from the Indonesian black bamboo species ''[[Gigantochloa atroviolacea]]'' by Professor Widjaja in 1997, as its appearance ([[Morphology (biology)|morphology]]) differed.<ref name="Widjaja97">{{cite journal | last=Widjaja | first=Elizabeth A | title=New taxa in Indonesian bamboo | journal=Reinwardtia | publisher=11 | pages=57–152 }}</ref>
