[[File:Lacus Spei 4165 h2.jpg|thumb|right|240px|Oblique view from [[Lunar Orbiter 4]]]]
[[File:Lacus Spei AS16-122-19606.jpg|thumb|left|240px|Oblique view from [[Apollo 16]]]]

'''Lacus Spei''' ([[Latin]] for "Lake of Hope") is a small [[lunar mare]] that is located in the northeastern part of the [[Moon]]'s near side. To the north is the crater [[Mercurius (crater)|Mercurius]] and to the west-southwest lies [[Schumacher (crater)|Schumacher]].

The selenographic [[coordinate]]s of this feature are 43.0° N, 65.0° E, and it lies within a diameter of 77&nbsp;km.<ref>[https://planetarynames.wr.usgs.gov/Feature/3218 Lacus Spei], Gazetteer of Planetary Nomenclature, International Astronomical Union (IAU) Working Group for Planetary System Nomenclature (WGPSN)</ref> The main part of the lake occupies a region averaging about 50&nbsp;km in diameter, with an extension leading to the northeast. The surface has the same low [[albedo]] as the larger mare features on the Moon, becoming lighter in hue near the edges. The only feature on this bay is the circular, cup-shaped satellite crater Zeno&nbsp;P. The crater [[Zeno (crater)|Zeno]] lies to the east-northeast, closer to the lunar limb.

